KEITH HARING + CITYKIDS X SOTHEBY’s 

We are delighted to share some incredible news with you; CityKids has partnered with Sotheby's. ‘Speak on Liberty,' the collaborative work of art by Keith Haring + 1,000 CityKids 'has been digitalized and will make its auction debut today, Thursday, December 15th. 
 
Over the past 34 years,  the significance of this collaborative work has continued to grow. Beginning with a cold call to Keith Haring from CityKids Founder Laurie Meadoff that brought together over 1,000 young people at the Javits center. 
 
‘Speak on Liberty’ has traveled the globe as the largest social justice calling card and a beacon for hope. 
 
'Speak on Liberty'referred to by Gil Vasquez, Executive Director of The Haring Foundation as "Keith's most impactful work"
 
As CityKids moved towards a future of new programming educating young people about the new economy, we became aware of the significance of preserving this monumental artifact for future generations. With the help of our partners at Seva.love and Immuse, we digitalized the original work of art and will be presenting it for sale as 1/1 NFT parcels beginning today at Sotheby's.
 
'Speak on Liberty #1' 
Keith Haring + CityKids, 1986
Estimated Value: 60,000-80,000 USD (Sotheby's)
Auction Date - 12/15 - 12-21
 
Profits raised from the sale will benefit CityKids.
 
If you would like to place a bid, visit https://lnkd.in/etAnsQid
 
Please join us in celebrating this incredible moment for the CityKids foundation by sharing this exciting news.

🌟Hey new friends! I'm Rachel Wilkins, a Web 3 strategist, CMO for Full Stackory, Founder of Conception Arts, and a @TIMEPieces council member. I'm super excited about the future of Web 3 and the incredible potential it holds! 

My journey has been filled with incredible opportunities, and I'm grateful to have received the New York Business Journal "Woman of Influence" Award and a New York State Citation for my work with the LGBTQ community. One of my passions is hosting the 'Good News Show,' a weekday Twitter Space and podcast where I get to share inspiring stories and engage in thought-provoking conversations with our amazing listeners.

Before diving into the world of Web 3, I co-founded Conception Arts, an organization that has supported over 5,000 artists across two continents. I also had the opportunity to host and produce the 'Smart Art Business' podcast, which has been recognized as a Top 2.5% show worldwide and listed in Apple Podcasts' Top 100 in 2019 and 2020.

My commitment to helping artists thrive led me to write "Sell Out: The Definitive Guide to Selling Your Art Online." I'm truly humbled by the "Arts Crusader" title given to me by the Huffington Post and grateful to have been featured by The Wall Street Journal, Paper Magazine, and ABC News.

I'm so excited to be part of this community, and I'm looking forward to learning from each of you and sharing my experiences. Together, let's grow, inspire, and create positive change in the world.

I can't tell you how much this piece by @robbiewilliams hits home. I've been acting all my life, not on stage, but hiding my social anxiety. Everyone thought I was the life of the party, but they didn't know that it was my buddy, alcohol, helping me get through it all for 15 long years.

Then, when I kicked the habit ten years ago, it was like someone had yanked off a plaster/band-aid from a super-sensitive part of me. I could feel EVERYTHING. I became like a human antenna picking up on all the vibes around me, and wow, was that draining!

Today, it's a bit of a lucky dip - some days, I'm owning the room, speaking to hundreds of people, and other days, I just want to crawl under the buffet table and disappear. But you know what? I'm learning to be okay with that. I've learned to take it easy on myself, no matter who turns up on the day – the social butterfly or the wallflower. 

I'm a work in progress, and that's totally fine by me. Grateful for every bit of this crazy ride.

I'm truly honored to be in conversation this morning with the remarkable Claire Silver, a trailblazer in the realm of AI-collaborative art.

Claire Silver, a celebrated name in the realm of art, is a luminary for the seamless fusion of tradition and technology in her works. Originating from a traditional art background, she has emerged as a pioneering figure in AI-collaborative art, challenging conventions and pushing boundaries to birth a new era of artistic expression. Her art, imbued with deeply human themes of vulnerability, trauma, and social hierarchy, interweaves these elements with a vision of our transhumanist future. Simultaneously, Claire has been a resolute supporter of other AI artists, lending her influence to elevate the entire field.

In addition to being an artist, Claire has been a visionary in the NFT space. As an early adopter of Cryptopunks, she has ardently advocated for the historical, cultural, and value-based propositions of NFTs. Claire's journey is not just about creating art, but about shifting paradigms and leading us into a new world where creativity meets technology.

In 2019, Conception Arts, the business I co-founded, was on track for its most successful year. By December, we had showcased over 1,000 artists across 14 cities. Yet, as the year neared its close, challenges arose. One of our City Directors departed for a new opportunity, while another fell ill. This series of events had me hastily booking flights to Texas to oversee our final two shows in Austin and Houston personally.

Arriving in Houston, the exhaustion from the year caught up with me, compounded by a sudden illness. Despite a restless night, I was responsible for setting up for our art show. By sheer determination, the event was successful, but I was running on fumes. The following day, I took a grueling bus ride to Austin, facing the same rigorous setup and an evening of celebration. Another successful event, but I was left utterly drained. On my 6 a.m. return flight to NYC, I silently pleaded for a break.

2020, however, delivered a break I hadn't envisioned. With its widespread devastation, the pandemic forced us to shutter Conception Arts since our entire revenue model was event-based. My loved ones and I were physically safe, but mentally, I spiraled. Battling the most severe depression and anxiety I'd faced in years, I confronted a stark truth: My identity and self-worth had become inextricably tied to my role as the director and co-founder of Conception Arts. When the company's doors closed, so did my sense of value.

The pandemic's reflection period revealed that for a decade, I'd overworked myself, equating professional achievements with personal worth. This revelation prompted a journey to decouple my self-worth from my accomplishments, a journey I'm still on.

A recent quote shared by my dear friend @JANPHILIPS resonated deeply: "Instead of asking, 'Have I worked hard enough to deserve this rest?' I now inquire, 'Have I rested enough to do my most loving and meaningful work?'" This mindset shift serves as a reminder: Only by nourishing oneself can we truly serve others at our highest capacity.

Embarrassed, my cheeks were red, and I wished the earth would swallow me whole. Yet, two invaluable lessons emerged from that humbling moment:

Earlier this year, I took the time to read Matthew's book. Being in recovery from myself, I've delved deep into numerous books on addiction, often gravitating towards personal narratives that share experiences, strength, and hope. However, nothing quite prepared me for the profound impact of Matthew's story.

His memoir is not just another tale of addiction. It's a gut-wrenching account of how drugs and alcohol can strip away every golden moment - from career accolades to personal relationships. Even with the world's best treatment options at his fingertips, the persistent cycle of relapse was devastating to witness. No amount of rehab stays, the fellow addicts he aided, or prolonged periods of sobriety could grant him a lasting escape.

In recovery circles, there's a saying that addiction, is akin to a relentless gorilla living in the basement doing push-ups, ever-ready to seize any moment of vulnerability. Today, with the news of Matthew's passing, this analogy resonates more than ever.

While the weight of his story is heavy on our hearts, I find solace in the fact that his brave and painfully honest narrative has played a role in my own journey and that of so many other addicts and alcoholics. It's a stark reminder that even in our strongest moments, we're only one bad decision away from potential relapse.

I genuinely hope Matthew has found the peace that eluded him in life. And if you're reading this, whether you're facing your own battles or know someone who is, I urge you to read his book. It might just inspire you to seek help, to persist in your recovery, or to view those struggling with addiction through a lens of deep compassion.

Let's keep the conversation on addiction going. It's a brutal, relentless disease, but with understanding and support, we can make a difference.

Rest in peace, Matthew. 🕊️

The power of picking a word has been life-changing for me. It was a concept introduced to me a few years back by a dear friend. 

🚀 In 2022, I chose “Abundance.” I said it out loud daily, and more than I bargained for came my way. 

🔮 2023 was “Magic,” and it truly delivered. From travel to magical humans, causes, and creativity, it was a year I will always treasure.

For the past few months, I thought “All In” would be my word for 2024, ready to commit with moxie to the things I love and need, and let go of the rest. But returning from the UK, I felt a bit upside down. Yesterday, a trusted friend asked me some big questions, unveiling some big, scary feelings. I realized how fear was leading my thoughts, and that wouldn’t do for accomplishing what I want in 2024. “Believe” or “Pride” came to mind, but they didn’t resonate fully. Then, in a church basement last night, I found my answer. 

💙 My word for the year is “TRUST.” Here’s what that means for me:

💙✨ Trusting Myself: Replacing self-doubt with self-assurance and believing in the universe’s support.

💙✨Trust in Others: Focusing on the good in people and giving the benefit of the doubt.

💙✨Trusting the Process: Embracing consistency, patience, and believing in incremental progress.

💙✨Trusting My Instincts: Listening to my inner voice as a guide to decision-making.

💙✨Trusting in Vulnerability: Being open about my feelings and needs, allowing deeper connections.

💙✨Trusting in Letting Go: Releasing what no longer serves me to make room for new beginnings.

💙✨Trusting in Reflection: Valuing silence and self-reflection for insights and peace.

💙✨Trusting My Body: Listening to its signals for better health and well-being.

💙✨Trusting in Adventure: Being open to new experiences and stepping out of my comfort zone.

💙✨Trusting My Creativity: Embracing and expressing myself without worrying about how my work will be received.

💙✨Trusting in Gratitude: Focusing on thankfulness. 

In 2024, “TRUST” is my beacon, guiding me through the year with confidence and an open heart.

Haters gonna hate, hate, hate, hate, hate... 

But let’s talk real about keyboard warriors, the unseen bullies of the digital world. We’ve all encountered them. I’ve had my share of virtual mudslinging, and it used to knock me down – not because they were right, but because I let their words weigh on me.

But here’s the thing: as I’ve journeyed into my 40s, I’ve learned to care less about others’ opinions.Here’s what works for me, and maybe it can work for you too (though, full disclosure, I sometimes still get it wrong):

1. Pause: In the immortal words of Meatloaf, “Let me sleep on it, baby, baby, let me sleep on it.” Reacting in the heat of the moment? Not always the best idea.

2. Empathy: Maybe that person lashing out is having a rough day, or year. Can I offer compassion instead of counter-attacks?

3. Silence: Sometimes, the most powerful response is no response. Silence can be golden.

Navigating online negativity isn’t easy, but remember, it’s about how we react that defines our experience.
